<task id="024" project="spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5">
  <metadata>
    <title>D2-14 Register `InsightsQueryToolHandler` (`insights.query`) on `SprkChatAgent`</title>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>4 hours</estimated-effort>
    <actual-effort></actual-effort>
    <assigned>AI Agent</assigned>
    <started></started>
    <completed></completed>
    <phase>Phase 2 — Vertical Slice + Insights Tool Integration</phase>
    <wave>P2-G6 (parallel-safe; first task of the Insights tool integration suite — deps 023; siblings 025, 026, 027, 028)</wave>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
    <dependencies>023 (R5 lead contract review + sign-off on `design-e3-tool-call-contract.md` v1.0 §10 — BLOCKING gate)</dependencies>
    <tags>bff, chat-agent, tool-registration, insights, ai</tags>
    <rigor-level>FULL</rigor-level>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Register a new `InsightsQueryToolHandler` chat-agent tool function on the existing
    `SprkChatAgent` via the established tool-registration mechanism (the
    `SprkChatAgentFactory.ResolveTools` site that already wires `AnalysisExecutionTools`,
    `DocumentSearchTools`, `WorkingDocumentTools`, and — once task 015 lands —
    `InvokeSummarizePlaybookTool` through `AIFunctionFactory.Create` and the AIPU2-061
    `CapabilityRouter` per-turn tool-injection contract). The tool exposes a single
    function (`InsightsQueryAsync`) with parameters `{ query: string, subject: string,
    forceMode?: string }` that POSTs to the Insights BFF endpoint
    `POST /api/insights/assistant/query` per binding contract v1.0
    (`notes/insights-engine-assistant-integration-brief.md`).

    R5 is a **Zone B consumer** of the Insights contract per refined ADR-013 §3.5 and
    R5 CLAUDE.md §3.5 / §10 "Don't inject Insights internals": this tool MUST call the
    HTTP endpoint via an HTTP client. It MUST NOT inject `IInsightsAi`,
    `InsightsOrchestrator`, `AssistantToolCallHandler`, `InsightsIntentClassifier`,
    `IRagService` Insights-specific extensions, or any other Insights-internal type
    directly. The Insights endpoint co-locates in the same BFF process today, but the
    boundary discipline is binding regardless — same-process HTTP is the canonical
    pattern for Zone B consumption.

    Tool description text is load-bearing for correct LLM routing (NFR-12) and MUST
    scope routing to "matter / project / invoice-scoped analytical questions about
    entities" — explicitly differentiated from `InvokeSummarizePlaybook` (task 015,
    file-scoped / session-scoped). This is the UR-01 mitigation flagged in plan.md High-
    Risk Items.

    The tool accepts an optional `forceMode` parameter: `null` (LLM tool-call leaves
    absent → BFF intent classifier runs server-side), `"playbook"` (slash command path
    knows intent), or `"rag"` (slash command path knows intent). Slash command path
    (task 019 `/ask-insights`) sets `forceMode` explicitly per spec FR-12 / SC-17;
    natural-language LLM tool-calls leave it absent.

    R5 is configuration-first + reuse-first: this task adds ZERO new top-level
    `Program.cs` lines, ZERO new feature flags (per ADR-018 + R5 CLAUDE.md §3.2), and
    ZERO new chat-agent / tool frameworks. Tool registration goes inside
    `AnalysisServicesModule.cs` (or — preferred per AIPL-053 precedent —
    in-factory tool-resolution block requiring no DI registration). The tool inherits
    the existing middleware stack (cost, content safety, telemetry, service routing)
    and the existing kill-switch coverage via `NullSprkChatAgentFactory` when Chat
    capability is disabled. The Insights endpoint itself enforces its own kill-switches
    (returns 503 `ai.insights.disabled` / `ai.rag.disabled` /
    `ai.intent-classification.disabled`) — this tool surfaces those errors to the user
    per the integration brief §5.1 error matrix.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior .NET developer with deep familiarity of the Spaarke chat-agent + AI-tool
    framework: `SprkChatAgentFactory.ResolveTools`, the `AIFunctionFactory.Create` tool
    registration pattern, the AIPU2-061 CapabilityRouter-driven per-turn tool injection,
    `CapabilityValidator`, `AnalysisServicesModule` DI conventions, `IHttpClientFactory`
    typed-client pattern, and the middleware stack (`AgentCostControlMiddleware`,
    `AgentContentSafetyMiddleware`, `AgentTelemetryMiddleware`,
    `AgentServiceRoutingMiddleware`). Understands ADR-013 (BFF-only AI; agents via
    factory; §3.5 Zone B consumer boundary), ADR-010 (feature-module DI minimalism),
    ADR-018 (no new feature flags), ADR-019 (ProblemDetails error parsing), ADR-028
    (no token snapshots — fresh OBO per request), ADR-016 (rate-limit honoring).
  </role>

  <goal>
    `InsightsQueryToolHandler` is registered as an `AIFunction` on every `SprkChatAgent`
    session via the existing `SprkChatAgentFactory.ResolveTools` mechanism
    (capability-gated alongside `AnalysisExecutionTools` / `WorkingDocumentTools` /
    `InvokeSummarizePlaybookTool`). The tool name is `insights.query` (exact).

    The tool's function (`InsightsQueryAsync`) accepts parameters `{ query: string,
    subject: string, forceMode?: string }` and POSTs them as JSON to
    `POST /api/insights/assistant/query` using an `IHttpClientFactory` typed client
    configured for the BFF base address, forwarding the active OBO bearer token (per
    ADR-028 — fresh from `HttpContext`, NOT snapshotted), generating + propagating an
    `x-correlation-id` header per Assistant turn (per spec FR-17 / SC-16), and parsing
    success / error responses per the contract v1.0 schema (integration brief §3 / §4 /
    §5). On success the tool returns the response payload (or a string-serialized
    summary suitable for the chat agent's conversation context); on error it surfaces
    a structured tool-error so the renderer (task 026) maps to per-code UX (integration
    brief §5.1). Both response paths (`path: "playbook"` and `path: "rag"`) are
    forwarded unchanged for downstream rendering by task 026's `InsightsResponseRenderer`.

    The LLM correctly tool-calls `insights.query` for natural-language matter/project/
    invoice analytical questions ("what will this matter cost?", "what closing
    conditions are in this matter?", "list outstanding invoices for project X") routed
    via the existing AIPU2-061 keyword + LLM capability router. The tool description
    text is curated specifically to scope routing to entity-scoped analytical questions
    and does NOT overlap semantically with `InvokeSummarizePlaybook` (task 015, scoped
    to chat-session uploaded-files Summarize).

    The `forceMode` parameter is correctly observed: slash command path (task 019)
    sets it (`"playbook"` or `"rag"` depending on slash invoked); LLM tool-calls leave
    it absent for natural-language routing through the BFF classifier. Verified by unit
    tests covering each path.

    The middleware stack (cost, safety, telemetry, service routing) wraps the tool
    execution inherited from `SprkChatAgentFactory.CreateAgent`; ZERO new `Program.cs`
    lines; ZERO new feature flags; ZERO Insights internals injected (verified via
    grep); BFF publish-size delta is measured + reported.
  </goal>

